Predicted decision boundaries:
<img src="/static/Module_1_Question_13_risk_vs_empirical_risk_figure_2.png" height="300" alt="The predicted decision boundary is a diagonal line through the unit box from the top left corner (0,1) to the bottom right corner (1,0). Class 0 prediction is the bottom triangle with vertices (0,1),(0,0) and (1,0) and class 1 prediction is the top triangle with vertices (0,1),(1,1) and (1,0). Within the Class 0 prediction area, there are two class 0 datapoints. Within the class 1 prediction area, there is one class 0 datapoint and two class 1 datapoints, for a total of 5 datapoints within the unit box."/>

( ) Risk = 1.0, Empirical risk = ⅕ {{Incorrect}}
( ) Risk = 0.5, Empirical risk = 1/2 {{Incorrect}}
( ) Risk = 0.75, Empirical risk = 0.75 {{Incorrect}}
(x) Risk = 0.5, Empirical risk = ⅕ {{Correct}}

>> At this point, what is the best action to do? <<

(x) Gather more data to capture better the true decision boundary. {{With this minimal number of points, the simplest model should be used. So the next action is to gather more data points.}}
( ) Increase the model complexity to reduce empirical risk. {{Increasing the model complexity with this limited number of points will overfit. We should use the most simple model and gather more data points.}}

